title: Ramda: Values<T> should not resolve as {}[], instead it should resolve to T[]
body:
This issue occurred due to some linting. It was assumed that

```ts
values<T>(obj: {[index: string]: T}): T[];
values<T>(obj: any): T[];
```
equals:

```ts
values<T>(obj: {[index: string]: T} | any): T[];
```

This doesn't seem to be the case. The argument will be resolved as any and values will return an {}[] instead.

So we have two options. We can either leave the additional definition in (breaking linting rules) or leave out the `any` entirely. This works for objects with string|numbers as keys, which should be %99.99 of the cases... unless I'm missing something.

This PR removes the any for the sake of simplicity. And adds some tests for the heck of it.

title: [node] Add inspector type definitions
body:
This change adds type definitions for `inspector`, which was introduced in Node v8.

The `inspector` API is a little unique: an inspector `Session` object can issue commands through `post` and listen for events, and the list of possible commands and events are defined in the [2nd documentation link](https://chromedevtools.github.io/devtools-protocol/v8/) in the checklist below. Commands always take their inputs and outputs as single objects. Sessions emit their data as a single object per event as well.

Because there are a limited number of commands and events, and each command/event's input/output object shapes are known at compile-time, I've taken the liberty of defining interfaces capturing the structure of each command input, command output, and event output. Most of the type definitions (when counting lines) consist of these interface definitions.

With this, we can get code completion like in the following image (which I think is nice):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2365820/29693309-b5ede958-88e9-11e7-8e2e-765d0c1b7428.png)

Most of the code is auto-generated from the [JSON file backing the 2nd documentation link](https://github.com/ChromeDevTools/devtools-protocol/blob/master/json/js_protocol.json). I believe the JSON file is auto-published as part of an npm package. (The auto-generation source code is located [here](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinietlyTyped/types/node/scripts/generate-inspector).)

I think it's important to introduce at least some form of type definitions for `inspector`. However, I'm concerned that this change adds a disproportionally large amount of code (~35% delta) for a relatively seldom-used module in Node. That, in combination with its auto-generated content, would likely compound on the maintenance burden for Node type definitions. So I'd like to ask any potential reviewers to weigh in on this: what is the best way to introduce type definitions for `inspector`?

I can think of a number of ways:

* Append comprehensive `inspector` type definitions to the end of `types/node/index.d.ts` (what this PR did when I first opened it)
* Add comprehensive `inspector` type definitions in a different `d.ts` file, and link it in `types/node/index.d.ts` (exactly what this PR is doing currently)
* Add basic type definitions (no auto-generated interfaces) here, and leave more comprehensive type definitions for a `@types/inspector` module (again, not sure if this is possible, since definitions may clash if someone installs both `@types/node` and `@types/inspector`)
* Add comprehensive type definitions as `@types/inspector`, and leave `@types/node` alone
